\parindent 0pt \parskip 6pt

Let the path of radiative transfer be divided into segments $[s_0,s_1],
\dots, [s_{i-1},s_i], \dots, [s_{n-1},s_n]$ where $s_0$ is the starting
point (usually space), and $s_n$ is the position of the observer.

The solution of the non-scattering radiative transfer equation,

\begin{equation}\label{one}
\frac{\d I(\nu,s)}{\d s} + \alpha(\nu,s)\, I(\nu,s) = \alpha(\nu,s) B(\nu,s)
\end{equation}

integrated on $[s_0,s_n]$, can be written

\begin{equation}\label{two}
I(\nu,s_n) = I(\nu,s_0)\, \T(\nu,s_0,s_n) +
             \int_{s_0}^{s_n} B(\nu,\sigma)\,\alpha(\nu,\sigma)\,
                                 \T(\nu,s_0,\sigma)\, \d \sigma
\end{equation}

where $I(s_0)$ is assumed to be indendependent of frequency (about 2.3
Kelvin), $B(\nu,\sigma)$ is the Planck radiation function (which depends
also upon temperature), $\alpha(\nu,\sigma)$ is the absortion cross
section (which depends also upon temperature), and

\begin{equation}\label{three}
\T(\nu,a,b) = \exp \left( - \int_a^b \alpha(\nu,s^\prime) \,\d s^\prime
                 \right) \,.
\end{equation}
 
The channel-averaged solution, the observed radiance, can be written

\begin{equation}
I_c(s_n) = \sum_{j \in c} c_j \left[ I(s_0)\, \T(\nu_j,s_0,s_n) +
           \int_{s_0}^{s_n} B(\nu_j,\sigma)\, \alpha(\nu_j,\sigma)\,
            \T(\nu_j,s_0,\sigma)\, \d \sigma \right]
\end{equation}

or

\begin{equation}\begin{split}\label{five}
I_c(s_n) =\,& \sum_j c_j \left[ \sum_{i=1}^n \left( I(s_0)\, 
                       \T(\nu_j,s_{i-1},s_i) +
                       \int_{s_{i-1}}^{s_i} B(\nu_j,\sigma)\,
                            \alpha(\nu_j,\sigma)\, \T(\sigma)\,
                            \d \sigma \right) \right] \\
       \approx\,& \sum_j c_j \left[
        \sum_{i=1}^n \left( I(s_0)\,  \T(\nu_j,s_{i-1},s_i) +
         \delta s_i \sum_k \omega_k B(\nu_j,s_k)\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_k)\,
          \T(\nu_j,s_0,s_k) \right) \right] \\
\end{split}\end{equation}

where $c_j$ is channel response at frequency $\nu_j$, $s_{i-1} \leq s_k
\leq s_i$, $\delta s_i = s_i - s_{i-1}$, and $\omega_k$ is a weight for a
quadrature formula.  We also assume $\sum_j c_j = 1$.

In the second term in Equation(\ref{five}),

\begin{equation}
\T(\nu_j,s_0,s_k) = \sum_{\ell=1}^{i-1} \T(\nu_j,s_{\ell-1},s_\ell) +
 \T(\nu_j,s_{i-1},s_k) \,.
\end{equation}

If trapezoidal quadrature is used, Equation(\ref{five}) becomes

\begin{equation}
I_c(s_n) = \sum_j c_j \left[
 \sum_{i=1}^n \left( I(s_0)\,  \T(\nu_j,s_{i-1},s_i) + I_{ij} \right) \right]
\end{equation}

where

\begin{equation}\begin{split}\label{eight}
I_{ij} = \,& \int_{s_{i-1}}^{s_i} B(\nu_j,\sigma)\, \alpha(\nu_j,\sigma)\,
 \T(\nu_j,s_0,\sigma) \, \d \sigma \\
 \approx \,&
         \frac12\, \delta s_i
          \left[ B(\nu_j,s_{i-1})\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_{i-1}) \T(\nu_j,s_0,s_{i-1}) +
                 B(\nu_j,s_i)\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_i) \T(\nu_j,s_0,s_i) \right] \\
 = \,& \frac12\, \delta s_i
        \left[ \T(\nu_j,s_0,s_{i-1})
        \left( B(\nu_j,s_{i-1})\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_{i-1}) + 
         B(\nu_j,s_i)\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_i) \right) + \right. \\
   \,& \hspace*{0.25in}\,\,\, \left. B(\nu_j,s_i)\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_i) \T(\nu_j,s_{i-1},s_i) \right] \\
 = \,&
       \frac12\, \delta s_i
       \left[ \left(\sum_{\ell=1}^{i-1} \T(\nu_j,s_{\ell-1},s_\ell) \right)
        \left( B(\nu_j,s_{i-1})\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_{i-1}) + 
         B(\nu_j,s_i)\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_i) \right) + \right. \\
   \,& \hspace*{0.3in}\,\,\,\,
        \Big.B(\nu_j,s_i)\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_i) \T(\nu_j,s_{i-1},s_i) \Bigg]\,. \\
\end{split}\end{equation}

Denoting $A_{ij} = B(\nu_j,s_i)\, \alpha(\nu_j,s_i)$ and $T_{ij} =
\mathcal{T}(\nu_j,s_{i-1},s_i)$, Equation (\ref{five}) becomes

\begin{equation}
I_c(s_n) \approx \sum_j c_j \left\{ \sum_{i=1}^n \left[ I(s_0) T_{ij} +
 \frac12\, \delta s_i \left(
 \left( A_{i-1,j} + A_{ij}\right)
  \sum_{\ell=1}^{i-1} T_{\ell j} + A_{ij} T_{ij} \right) \right] \right\}\,.
\end{equation}

Denoting $\hat{T}_{i} = \sum_j c_j T_{ij}$ and $\hat{B}_i = \sum_j c_j A_{ij}$,
and further approximating the average of a product by the product of the
averages of its factors, Equation (\ref{five}) becomes

\begin{equation}\label{ten}
I_c(s_n) \approx I(s_0) \sum_{i=1}^n\hat{T}_i + \sum_{i=1}^n \left[
 \frac12\, \delta s_i \left( (\hat{A}_{i-1}+\hat{A}_i)
   \sum_{\ell=1}^{i-1} \hat{T}_i + \hat{A}_i \hat{T}_i \right) \right] \,,
\end{equation}

in which $\hat{T}_i$ appears linearly.

$\hat{T}_i$ is an integral through a parcel of the atmosphere.  In two
dimensions, the parcel can be taken to be a rectangle in $\phi \times
\zeta$, or in three dimensions, it can be taken to be a triangular prism
grounded in one QTM facet and bounded vertically by two constant-$\zeta$
surfaces.

If there are sufficient independent lines-of-sight through each parcel, a
system of Equations (\ref{ten}) can be solved for $\hat{T}_i$.

Making the further assumption that Equation (\ref{three}) can be
approximated by

\begin{equation}
\hat{T}_i \approx \exp \left( - \int_{s_{i-1}}^{s_i}
                            \alpha(\nu,s^\prime) \, \d s^\prime \right)
\end{equation}

for some frequency $\nu$ within the channel,

\begin{equation}\label{twelve}
\ln \hat{T}_i \approx -\int_{s_{i-1}}^{s_i} \alpha(\nu,s^\prime) \, \d s^\prime
\end{equation}

Replacing the integral in Equation (\ref{twelve}) with a cubature, and
expanding $\alpha$ in terms of individual species, Equation (\ref{twelve})
can be written

\begin{equation}\label{thirteen}
\ln \hat{T}_i \approx -\Delta \sum_k f_i^k \, \beta_i^k(\nu) \,,
\end{equation}

where $k$ is a species index and $\Delta$ is the area or volume of the
$i^\text{th}$ parcel of atmosphere, and $\beta_i^k(\nu)$ is the absorption
coefficient for species $k$ at some average temperature within the
$i^\text{th}$ parcel of the atmosphere.  Notice that $f_i^k$ appears
linearly.

If the observations and estimated radiances $I_c(s_n)$ are divided into a
number of subsets, at least as many as the number of species, Equation
(\ref{thirteen}) can be solved for an estimate for $f_i^k$.  Using this as
an initial estimate, It is likely that Equation (\ref{one}) could be
solved for $f_i^k$ using the present nonlinear method with fewer
iterations.

Once a solution of Equation (\ref{thirteen}) for $f_i^k$ is in hand, there
are two possibilities:

\begin{itemize}

\item If the solution of Equation (\ref{thirteen}) for $f_i^k$ is sufficiently
accurate, the covariance of the solution would need to be converted from
the covariance of a log-normal distribution to a normal distribution. 
Then insert $f_i^k$ into Equation (\ref{one}) or (\ref{two}) and solve for
temperature.

\item If the solution of Equation (\ref{thirteen}) for $f_i^k$, or the
subsequent solution of Equation (\ref{one}) or (\ref{two}) for
temperature, is not sufficiently accurate, there are two further
possibilities:

  \begin{itemize}

  \item Use $f_i^k$ as a starting point to solve Equation (\ref{one}) or
  (\ref{two}) for temperature and a better estimate for $f_i^k$.

  \item Use $f_i^k$ as a starting point to solve Equation
  (\ref{one}) or (\ref{two}) for temperature, then use that estimate for
  temperature to solve Equation(\ref{thirteen}) for a revised estimate for
  $f_i^k$, and repeat.

  \end{itemize}
  
  If a final combined solution of Equation (\ref{one}) or
  (\ref{two}) for temperature and mixing rations is performed, the
  covariance is the normal covariance, not log normal.

\end{itemize}

